      <bioghist id="aspace_e3d0060f9ac9961f3627ccf4a4bd7772">
         <head>Ray Livingston Murphy (1923-1953)</head>
         <p>Ray Livingston Murphy was a scholar and collector of literature and art. In 1948, he published <title>
               <part>Last Viceroy: The Life and Times of Rear-Admiral The Earl Mountbatten of Burma</part>
            </title>.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <bioghist id="aspace_d4c6874e557a19e5fb00f37e5935b304">
         <head>Edward Bulwer Lytton, Baron Lytton (1803-1873)</head>
         <p>Edward Bulwer-Lytton, 1st Baron Lytton, was an English author and politician. His works include the novels <title>
               <part>Pelham: or The Adventures of a Gentleman</part>
            </title> (1828), <title>
               <part>Godolphin</part>
            </title> (1833), <title>
               <part>A Strange Story</part>
            </title> (1862), and <title>
               <part>Kenelm Chillingly</part>
            </title> (1873), and the plays <title>
               <part>Richelieu</part>
            </title> (1839) and <title>
               <part>Not So Bad as We Seem, or, Many Sides to a Character: A Comedy in Five Acts</part>
            </title> (1851). He served as a Whig Member of Parliament from 1831 to 1841 and as a Conservative from 1851 to 1866.</p>
         <p>In 1827, Bulwer-Lytton married Irish-born author Rosina Doyle Wheeler. They had two children, Emily Elizabeth Bulwer-Lytton and Edward Robert Bulwer-Lytton. The couple legally separated in 1836. In 1858, Lytton accused Rosina of being insane, and she was briefly hospitalized against her will.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_73e0d5473fcbfbb7f9851e043cbc76ce">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Ray Livingston Murphy Collection of Edward Robert Bulwer-Lytton, Baron Lytton. General Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <processinfo id="aspace_684253ce19cf43212fd9e03005fa0e89">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Former call number: MS Vault Lytton</p>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected.  The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.</p>
         <p>This collection received a basic level of processing, including rehousing and minimal organization.</p>
         <p>Information included in the Description of Papers note and Collection Contents section is drawn from information supplied with the collection and from an initial survey of the contents. Folder titles appearing in the contents list below are often based on those provided by the creator or previous custodian. Titles have not been verified against the contents of the folders in all cases. Otherwise, folder titles are supplied by staff during initial processing.</p>
         <p>This finding aid may be updated periodically to account for new acquisitions to the collection and/or revisions in arrangement and description.</p>
      </processinfo>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_e493c1f11a797b9f86e3710c2bea59e5">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection consists of writings, correspondence, and legal documents by or relating to English author and politician Edward Bulwer-Lytton. Included is a volume containing publishing agreements and correspondence, dummies of title pages, and copyright information for Bulwer-Lytton's novels; and autograph manuscript poems to be incorporated into <title>
               <part>Pausanius, the Spartan</part>
            </title>, a novel by Bulwer-Lytton published posthumously. The collection also contains proofs of <title>
               <part>Not So Bad as We Seem</part>
            </title>; autograph manuscript drafts of "Confessions and Observations of a Water Patient," published in <title>
               <part>New Monthly Magazine</part>
            </title>, and act one of a play based on Bulwer-Lytton's book <title>
               <part>Kenelm Chillingly</part>
            </title>; and an agreement with Charles Dickens and others to publish <title>
               <part>A Strange Story</part>
            </title> in Great Britain and the United States. Correspondence consists primarily of letters from Bulwer-Lytton, his wife, novelist Rosina Bulwer-Lytton, and their son, poet and diplomat Edward Robert Bulwer-Lytton, to various recipients. Lady Lytton's letter to her solicitor Charles Hyde, written several months after Baron Lytton had her incarcerated in a psychiatric facility, references her financial situation and anger at her estranged husband. Also included is a bound volume of letters to and from the author Sydney Owenson, known as Lady Morgan.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_fd17acdaba572126a9de83011c8c7483">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The Ray Livingston Murphy Collection of Edward Robert Bulwer-Lytton, Baron Lytton is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.</p>
      </userestrict>
